Today on the blog! Something I'm excited (and nervous) to share: How to Create a Birth Wish List. If you've heard my birth story (which I'll be sharing on Friday), you know that I struggled with the loss of my birth "plan." I don't want any of you to go through that so I wrote a post that may help you "plan" with a more openness to the unpredictability of birth.

New episode! Lindsey Bliss @doulabliss is the co-director of @CarriageHouseBirth, an experienced birth doula, and the mother of seven. Lindsey is considered to be a multiples expert after giving birth to and parenting two consecutive sets of twins. Lindsey takes on her role as a birth doula and childbirth educator with serious passion and commitment. Her mission is to hold space for expectant families through education and informed decision making. Being prepared, and knowing what options are available increases the likelihood of an amazing birth. Lindsey facilitates that process, giving people the tools and inspiration to empower themselves. Her unwavering support and gentle guidance have benefited over two hundred families. Lindsey supports first time parents, multiparas, single parents, LGBT families, twins births, medicated and non medicated vaginal births, cesarean births, and VBACs. Click the profile link or search The Birth Hour in iTunes or your favorite podcast app to listen. 🎧

'She came!  It happened!  I did it!' How many of you said something similar in the first moments after birth? 📷reposted from @tallgrassphotographybychant
・・・
Tears are dripping down your cheeks, your thighs have a tint of blood on them and there's a deep, damp, musky metallic smell in the room. You feel drained and soft; there's burning and pounding, yet you are taken away by the delicious lightness and ecstasy of oxytocin and the sweet relief of your baby's skin glued to your chest. She feels warm and plump, and the scent of her head arrows straight into your heart. You watch in amazement as she latches on for the first time. You feel her taking in some of that bosom nectar that you have been carefully preparing for her and you suddenly feel whole. "She came! It happened! I did it!"
